    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>As other answers note, the correct way to find the Java home directory is to use <code>/usr/libexec/java_home</code>.</p>\n\n<p>The official documentation for this is in Apple's <em>Technical Q&amp;A QA1170: Important Java Directories on OS X</em>: <a href=\"https://developer.apple.com/library/mac/qa/qa1170/_index.html\" rel=\"nofollow\">https://developer.apple.com/library/mac/qa/qa1170/_index.html</a></p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 187852,
      "reputation" : 753,
      "user_id" : 426209,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 75,
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/01e14274f05ab4d429eae709835374ca?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "Yichuan Wang",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/426209/yichuan-wang"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : -1,
    "last_activity_date" : 1461805285,
    "creation_date" : 1461805285,
    "answer_id" : 36903447,
    "question_id" : 1348842,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>For Fish Shell users, use something like the following: <code>alias java7 \"set -gx JAVA_HOME (/usr/libexec/java_home -v1.7)\"</code></p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 73312,
      "reputation" : 5821,
      "user_id" : 211197,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/3025c47fb787c22515e85ec57a95b9c7?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "maksimov",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/211197/maksimov"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 2,
    "last_activity_date" : 1478632955,
    "creation_date" : 1478632955,
    "answer_id" : 40494854,
    "question_id" : 1348842,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>For me maven seems to work off the <code>.mavenrc</code> file:</p>\n\n<pre><code>echo \"export JAVA_HOME=$(/usr/libexec/java_home -v 1.8)\" &gt; ~/.mavenrc\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>I'm sure I picked it up on SO too, just can't remember where.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "comments" : [ {
      "owner" : {
        "account_id" : 3612523,
        "reputation" : 9292,
        "user_id" : 3013206,
        "user_type" : "registered",
        "accept_rate" : 20,
        "profile_image" : "https://i.sstatic.net/m2eqI.png?s=256",
        "display_name" : "Spindizzy",
        "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/3013206/spindizzy"
      },
      "edited" : false,
      "score" : 1,
      "creation_date" : 1540636564,
      "post_id" : 41367448,
      "comment_id" : 92944333,
      "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
      "body" : "I like this approach, because it allows me to change the Java version very easy within the .mavenrc file."
    } ],
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 3733569,
      "reputation" : 5582,
      "user_id" : 3105145,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://i.sstatic.net/3VA8j.jpg?s=256",
      "display_name" : "KhaledMohamedP",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/3105145/khaledmohamedp"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 5,
    "last_activity_date" : 1482948437,
    "creation_date" : 1482948437,
    "answer_id" : 41367448,
    "question_id" : 1348842,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>Create file <code>~/.mavenrc</code></p>\n\n<p>then paste this into the file </p>\n\n<p><code>export JAVA_HOME=$(/usr/libexec/java_home)</code></p>\n\n<p>test</p>\n\n<p><code>mvn -v</code></p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 259035,
      "reputation" : 13175,
      "user_id" : 541624,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 64,
      "profile_image" : "https://i.sstatic.net/uyz2B.jpg?s=256",
      "display_name" : "ericn",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/541624/ericn"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 2,
    "last_activity_date" : 1497175483,
    "creation_date" : 1497175483,
    "answer_id" : 44482574,
    "question_id" : 1348842,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>Skipping Terminal setup since you mentioned applications, permanent system environment variable set up (works for macOS Sierra; should work for El Capitan too):  </p>\n\n<pre><code>launchctl setenv JAVA_HOME $(/usr/libexec/java_home -v 1.8)\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>(this will set JAVA_HOME to the latest 1.8 JDK, chances are you have gone through serveral updates e.g. javac 1.8.0_101, javac 1.8.0_131)<br>\nOf course, change 1.8 to 1.7 or 1.6 (really?) to suit your need and your system  </p>\n"
  }, {
    "comments" : [ {
